After you have explored completely, submit the three graphs/plots that you found most informative during your EDA process, and briefly explain what you learned from each (why you found each informative).

0.1.1 I found it very helpful to to look at the pricing of homes when grouping by neighborhood using a box and whisker plot. This allowed me to observe the level of variation, as well as the mean and quartiles within each neighborhood of the city.

0.1.2 This second box and whisker plot of price grouped by zoning was similarly as helpful as the the prior plot. I was able to see that low- and medium- depsity had much more variation in price relative to the other types of zoning.

0.1.3 Finally, for the 3rd helpful graph shows a scatter plot relationship between price and area of homes with a linear regression line the shows the positive association between these two variables. This graph also shows many large homes with relatively low pricing (under linear regression line) which might be homes worth looking at a little closer.

Since I already know that area is positively associated with price I included is as a predictor in this model (also just using basic intution here). I also used my intutition to that zoning, year.built, overall.qual, year.remod.add, and lot.area were also likely key predictors in pricing. For neighborhood and land.slope I was more just curious to see if they are reasonable predictor variables.

0.2.3 We can see that area, Lot.Area, Year.Built, Overall.Qual, and Year.Remod.add are all significant predictors for price. Also, 8 certain neighborhoods are good at predicting price, as well as MS.ZoningRL and moderate or severe land slope.

0.2.4 Section 2.2 Model Selection

Now either using BAS or another stepwise selection procedure choose the best model you can, using your initial model as your starting point. Try at least two different model selection methods and compare their results. Do they both arrive at the same model or do they disagree? What do you think this means?

When using BAS selection, inclusion probabilities of area, certain neighborhoods, certain zoning, lot.area, year.built overall.qual, yera.remod, land.slope are all relatively high (close or equal to 1.0). When using stepwise backward elimination, area, certain neighborhoods, certain zoning, lot.area, year.built, overall.qual, year.remod.add, and land.slope all have p-values less than 0.05. This means that both of the models agree with each other. I think this means they are both effective methods for model selection.

0.2.5 Section 2.3 Initial Model Residuals

One way to assess the performance of a model is to examine the models residuals. In the space below, create a residual plot for your preferred model from above and use it to assess whether your model appears to fit the data well. Comment on any interesting structure in the residual plot (trend, outliers, etc.) and briefly discuss potential implications it may have for your model and inference / prediction you might produce.

0.2.6 Theres a propensity to underpredict for higher fitted values (greater than $250,000). The model also appears to be generally well-fitted for homes under $250,000. There is one extreme outlier and a handful more that could be argued to outliers.

0.2.7 If theres a propensity to underpredict for higher fitted values, the model should be used with great caution if the firm is looking to purchase these higher-valued homes.

residuals2.2.2<-resid(model2.2.2)
df2.2.2<-fortify(model2.2.2)
options(scipen = 999)
ggplot(df2.2.2, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) + geom_point()

0.4.1 Section 4.1 Final Model Residual

For your final model, create and briefly interpret an informative plot of the residuals.

0.4.2 In large, the model error has reduced and the discrepency for high valued properties (above $250,000) has declined, however there was one extreme outlier that I removed in the second residul graph.

predictions4.1<-exp(predict(model3.1,ames_train))
residuals4.1<-ames_train$price-predictions4.1
df4.1<-data.frame(.fitted=predictions4.1,.resid=residuals4.1)
ggplot(df4.1, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) + geom_point() # Add Labels

# Residuals with out extreme outlier
residuals4.1nooutlier<-residuals4.1[residuals4.1>min(residuals4.1)]
predictions4.1nooutlier<-predictions4.1[predictions4.1<max(predictions4.1)]
df4.1nooutlier<-data.frame(.fitted=predictions4.1nooutlier,.resid=residuals4.1nooutlier)
ggplot(df4.1nooutlier, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) + geom_point() # Add Labels

Provide a brief summary of your results, and a brief discussion of what you have learned about the data and your model.

0.5.1 I learned that the model is more rubust than the first model, yet the model has an inability to predict with new categorical variables that were not in the training set, anbd its accuracy declines for properties beyond $250,000. Also the error for validation is smaller than training, which proves the models utility. The model was capable of making accurate predictions on unseen data as evidence by a decline in model error. The model appears to accurately represent the esimated uncertainty of it predictions. The uncertainty around the price can sometimes be large enough that investors should understand that there is still some risk in property investment when using the model to make purchasing decisions.
